-- Crude Options Volatility Increases as Oil Futures Retreat
-- B y   B a r b a r a   P o w e l l
-- 2013-07-24T18:15:01Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-07-24/crude-options-volatility-increases-as-oil-futures-retreat.html
Crude options volatility rose as
September futures fell the most in more than a month.  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
September, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a
gauge of options value, was 22.42 percent on the  New York
Mercantile Exchange  as of 1:48 p.m., up from 21.36 yesterday.  West Texas Intermediate crude for September delivery fell
$2.08, or 1.9 percent, to $105.15 a barrel on the Nymex, the
biggest loss since June 20.  The most active options in electronic trading today were
September $100 puts, which rose 31 cents to 73 cents a barrel on
volume of 6,864 lots traded as of 1:53 p.m. September $95 puts
were the second-most active, advancing 10 cents to 23 cents on
volume of 2,599 contracts.  Puts accounted for 65 percent of electronic trading volume.
In the prior session, calls made up 54 percent of 131,442
contracts exchanged.  October $107.50 calls were the most-active options
yesterday with 5,283 contracts changing hands as they fell 3
cents to $2.69 a barrel. October $112.50 calls declined 7 cents
to $1.11 on 5,271 lots.  Open interest was highest for December $80 puts, with
38,346 contracts. Next were December $90 puts with 37,685 lots
and December $70 puts with 35,655.  The exchange distributes real-time data for electronic
trading and releases information the next business day on open-outcry volume, where the bulk of options activity occurs.  To contact the reporter on this story:
